reviewText: This was an interesting, sensitive and artistic look at the female form. Not exactly a typical coffee table book. It could be quite useful to a OBGYN for women who are considering plastic surgery in that area. From a female perspective, this may be important to examen. But from a male perspective, it is still erotic, since it separates the female personality from her sex organ. No getting around it. He even said it's not primarily for men. From a documentary critique, it is very heavy with dialogue from sex experts - some important ones in the second half. It would have been good to get some public views on the book. But it can be a lot of work to produce a documentary. The main difference with this view and a commercial sex product is that these women were not chosen to be in the book because they are beauty queens, models. And the presentation is not glossy, saturated color.
summary: artistic but erotic look at female form

reviewText: So many women and men have been schooled that a woman's "Petals" are a mark of sin, ugly, a foul place, that many women are ashamed to be seen in their glory.  This video is uplifting in the same way Vagina Monologues is uplifting.  My wife and I have shared this with daughter and daughter-in-law.  Daughter-in-law not quite ready to share it with her daughter and says she will at some point.  Long before this video, in our house, Petals were referred to as the Blossom, the symbol of creation.
summary: A primer on how to honor the beauty that the goddess provides
